    "preparations_description": "The main herbal preparations of Angelica dentata are tincture, tea, infusion, salve, and decoction. Tincture is a concentrated liquid extract used to treat digestive issues and colds, typically prepared by steeping the dried root in a solvent like ethanol. Tea is made by infusing the dried root in hot water, often consumed to alleviate menstrual cramps and as a diuretic. Infusion involves steeping the root in cold water to create a calming tea, used for anxiety and insomnia relief. Decoction, a boiling method, is used to extract the root's active compounds, commonly employed to treat arthritis and rheumatism due to its anti-inflammatory properties.",
