    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effect of using Angelica dentata are gastrointestinal issues, such as nausea and diarrhea, due to the presence of sesquiterpene lactones and angelan, which can irritate the stomach lining and induce gastrointestinal upset. Allergic reactions to Angelica dentata can also occur, leading to symptoms like hives, itching, and difficulty breathing, particularly in individuals with pre-existing allergies. The improper use of Angelica dentata may also cause nausea due to the emetic properties of its sesquiterpene lactones, which can stimulate the vomiting center in the brain. Developing diarrhea is another possible side effect, as the angelan in Angelica dentata can alter the balance of gut bacteria and disrupt normal bowel function. Prolonged or excessive use of Angelica dentata can exacerbate these side effects and lead to more severe health issues.",
    "uses": "Angelica dentata, a species of angelica native to China, has been used in traditional medicine for various purposes. The plant is rich in bioactive compounds, including coumarins, lignans, and volatile oils, which contribute to its medicinal properties. It has been traditionally used to treat fever, rheumatism, and digestive issues, as well as to relieve pain and inflammation. The plant's roots and rhizomes are often used in herbal remedies due to their high concentration of bioactive compounds. Further research is needed to fully understand the efficacy and potential side effects of using Angelica dentata for medicinal purposes.",
    "taxonomy": "Angelica dentata is classified as a member of the carrot family (Apiaceae), within the genus Angelica. This plant is native to Asia and is also known as Japanese angelica or Tohon. It is further classified as Angelica dentata within the species. Angelica dentata is often divided into two subspecies: A. d. dentata and A. d. tsukusimana. The classification is based on its botanical characteristics and distribution.",
    "benefits": "Angelica dentata, also known as toothed angelica, has been used in traditional medicine for its potential health benefits. The plant is rich in vitamins, minerals, and antioxidants, which may help to boost the immune system and reduce inflammation. Its roots and leaves have been used to treat various ailments, including digestive issues, fever, and respiratory problems. Some studies suggest that Angelica dentata may have anti-inflammatory, antimicrobial, and antiviral properties. However, more research is needed to confirm its full range of health benefits and potential interactions with medications.",
    "parts": "Angelica dentata, also known as Toyo-shiksa or Japanese angelica, is a plant native to East Asia. The medicinal parts of Angelica dentata include the root and rhizome, which are commonly used in traditional medicine. The root and rhizome contain compounds like ferulic acid, which is believed to have anti-inflammatory properties. In traditional Chinese medicine, the plant is used to treat various health conditions, including fever, cough, and digestive issues. The plant's medicinal properties are also attributed to its ability to stimulate blood circulation and reduce swelling.",
    "intro": "Angelica dentata, also known as Chinese Angelica or Dong Quai, is a perennial plant native to China, belonging to the carrot family (Apiaceae). The plant is valued for its medicinal properties, particularly for its ability to promote digestion, reduce menstrual cramps, and alleviate symptoms of menopause, such as hot flashes and night sweats. The bioactive constituents of Angelica dentata include ligustilide, butylphthalide, and ferulic acid, which contribute to its therapeutic effects. The most common herbal preparations made with Angelica dentata include teas, capsules, and tinctures, which are often used to support women's health and relieve various symptoms associated with PMS and menopause."
